      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Diplomats and United Nations officials have been discussing the possibility that thousands of refugees now in southern Iraq may be admitted into Kuwait, Iran and Saudi Arabia, United Nations officials said here today.</p>
        <p>There are some 30,000 refugees in the south of Iraq, many of whom backed an unsuccessful Shiite Muslim uprising there. The refugees have been under the protection of the coalition that drove Iraqi forces from Kuwait, but the coalition's troops are being pulled out of the area.</p>
        <p>One official said he assumed the movement of refugees would be completed before Iraq re-established control over the zone.</p>
        <p>The United Nations officials said here today that discussions about moving the refugees have been held in recent days here and in the capitals of the countries involved.</p>
        <p>Officials estimated that roughly 4,000 of the 30,000 were Iranian Shiite Muslims or Shiite Iraqi nationals of Iranian descent with relatives in Iran. They said the number of Iraqi Sunni Muslims among the 30,000 was something less than 4,000.</p>
        <p>AFTER THE WAR</p>
